edu.ncsu.csc.Galant.algorithm.code.macro

Class ParameterizedMacro

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.ncsu.csc.Galant.algorithm.code.macro.Macro
      • edu.ncsu.csc.Galant.algorithm.code.macro.ParameterizedMacro

  • public abstract class ParameterizedMacro
extends Macro

    A macro of the form:
    name(param1, param2, ... )

    Matches immediately following Java identifier parts are ignored: for example, if the name is "macro", then "a_macro(…)" won't be counted as a match.

    Subclasses of this class should override modifyMatch(String, MatchResult, String[], String, String) rather than modify(String, MatchResult), since this class needs to include some functionality in the latter.

      • ParameterizedMacro

        public ParameterizedMacro(java.lang.String name,
                  int minParams,
                  int maxParams,
                  boolean includeCodeBlock)
        Creates a new ParameterizedMacro. minParams and maxParams determine the number of parameters allowed; if the actual number of parameters is less than minParams or greater than maxParams, a MalformedMacroException will be thrown. If maxParams is negative or minParams > maxParams, any number of parameters will be accepted.
        Parameters:
        name - the name of the macro (can be a regex).
        minParams - the minimum number of parameters the macro should take.
        maxParams - the maximum number of parameters the macro should take.

      • modify

        protected final java.lang.String modify(java.lang.String code,
                      java.util.regex.MatchResult match)
                                 throws MalformedMacroException
        Description copied from class: Macro

        Subclasses should implement this method and return a modified version of the current match. The returned string will be used as a replacement string for Matcher.appendReplacement(StringBuffer, String), with the syntax described in the javadoc for that method. So backslashes and dollar signs may need to be escaped.

        If the match is not actually correct, null can be returned. (This can be used with the default applyTo without creating an infinite loop.)

        Note: Macros may add new macros to the end of the macro list (e.g., by creating new macros), but other modifications to the list may not be supported.

        Specified by:
        modify in class Macro
        Parameters:
        code - the user code on which this macro is being applied.
        match - a match of this macro's pattern.
        Returns:
        the replacement of the matched region, or null if the match is not actually valid.
        Throws:
        MalformedMacroException - if the match is not a valid invocation of this macro, but it should have been.

      • modifyMatch

        protected abstract java.lang.String modifyMatch(java.lang.String code,
                           java.util.regex.MatchResult nameMatch,
                           java.lang.String[] args,
                           java.lang.String whitespace,
                           java.lang.String block)
        See Macro.modify(String, MatchResult). The difference is that instead of being given a MatchResult, the implementation is given an array of arguments.
        Parameters:
        code - the user code on which this macro is being applied.
        nameMatch - the result of matching the pattern passed in as the name to the part of the overall match that matched that pattern. The main reason for this is access to any capturing groups in the name.
        args - the arguments passed to this macro.
        whitespace - the whitespace between the parameters and the code block (to keep the same number of lines), or null if the code block is not included.
        block - the code in the code block, or null if the code block is not included.
